<TEXT>
disgraced former president chun 
doohwan ended two years of selfimposed exile in a remote mountain 
temple sunday to return to seoul and almost certain political 
controversy 
chun who was accompanied by his wife and aides left the 14th 
century buddhist temple in the snowcapped eastern mountains with a 
police escort news reports said 
about 2500 riot police blocked streets and alleyways near 
chuns house in western seoul to check identifications and prevent 
possible protests opponents attacked the house repeatedly before 
chuns departure it has remained under heavy guard during his 
exile 
in the future i will continue to live as an ordinary 
citizen said the former general in a statement at the temple 
dissidents have asked the government to prosecute chun 
contending he ordered the military to crush a 1980 prodemocracy 
uprising in kwangju by official count about 200 people were 
killed in the uprising 
the former president left seoul to go into rural exile in 
november 1988 after apologizing on national television for abuses 
of power during his seven year rule which ended in 1987 
chun left office after accepting opposition demands for direct 
popular elections following mass antigovernment protests in 1987 
he handpicked roh taewoo as the governing party candidate and 
roh won the presidency by a narrow margin in december 1987 
roh a former general who helped chun seize power in 1980 has 
appealed to the nation for mercy for chun a dozen of chuns 
relatives and associates have been convicted of corruption and 
imprisoned since roh took office 
