<TEXT>
two army deserters who hijacked an 
airliner and held dozens of hostages during a twoday standoff 
surrendered sunday after freeing all passengers and crew the 
official algerian news agency reported 
the hijackers were taken into custody without violence after 
releasing the pilot and copilot of the stateowned air algerie 
boeing 737 the news agency said earlier 46 remaining passengers 
were freed 
there were no reports of injuries 
the hijackers names were not immediately released by 
authorities and the motive for the incident was unclear the aps 
news agency reported the men were deserters from the saharan town 
of ghardaia where the flight began late friday 
the hijackers who were armed had demanded 20 hours worth of 
fuel to fly to another country 
the jet carrying 82 passengers and six crew members was forced 
to land in the eastern city of annaba early saturday after 
officials in carthage tunisia turned the flight away 
egyptian officials refused saturday to allow the hijackers to 
fly there 
the hijackers seized the aircraft shortly after takeoff from 
ghardaia a popular winter resort it was bound for the algerian 
capital of algiers 
according to airline officials and accounts by freed passengers 
the pair produced a pistol and submachine gun shortly after 
takeoff one hijacker took control of the cabin and the other 
watched over the passengers forcing the women to the front of the 
plane 
the plane started rolling but not like an air pocket 
french passenger paulette thibule 67 told the french television 
network la cinq the stewardesses got moving toward the front 
thats when i understood there was a struggle in the cockpit 
talks with the hijackers resumed at dawn sunday 
interior minister mohammad saleh mohammedi first negotiated the 
release of the remaining people on board a short while later he 
persuaded the two men to surrender witnesses said the hijackers 
gave up after freeing the pilot and copilot 
