<TEXT>
mayor david dinkins reflecting on his first 
year in office says hes proud that he maintained the citys bond 
rating despite a budget deficit 
but the citys first black mayor said he wishes he could have 
spent less time dealing with fiscal problems and more time on the 
social issues that propelled him into office 
i look forward to the day when we will be able to move ahead 
on some of the dreams that have been for the moment at least 
deferred dinkins said during a recent interview 
a projected gap of at least 250 million in the citys 1991 
fiscal year budget has forced the mayor to cut funds in virtually 
every area from education and street cleaning to libraries and 
bridge repair 
according to a federal report released the week before 
christmas the new york metropolitan region lost an estimated 
100000 jobs in private industry in 1990 half of them in new york 
city 
the fiscal crisis has made it difficult for dinkins to devote 
time to the citys poor and young whose plight he promised to 
improve during his campaign for mayor 
dinkins acknowledged that his inability to focus on social 
issues has made some of his strongest supporters impatient for 
results 
a recent new york newsday poll showed that only 33 percent of 
those interviewed approved of his job performance down from 53 
percent in june the biggest decline in approval came among blacks 
still largely supportive of him but down to 65 percent from 76 
percent and manhattan residents 
dinkins said the high points of his first year included 
antiapartheid leader nelson mandelas visit a decision by the 
democratic party to hold its 1992 convention here and his city 
hall speech calling for racial harmony as new yorkers awaited a 
verdict in the first trial in the slaying of a black teenager in a 
mob attack in a predominantly white neighborhood in brooklyn 
while the citys crime rate has soared with annual city murders 
topping 2000 for the first time dinkins said he is proud of his 
safe streets safe city plan to hire thousands of new police 
officers 
but he failed to win the approval of the crime plan by the state 
legislature which recessed two weeks ago without acting on it 
asked about his priorities for 1992 the mayor said he would 
focus first on fiscal stability followed by public safety and then 
education youth services and health care 
there are many more things i had hoped to accomplish 
especially in the areas of human service that just plain require 
money dinkins admitted 
